<font color="#FF0000">SOMEONE TO SPEAK FOR THEM</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jan  6  8:18:29 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Mike, OK, agree on the sampan scene.  Still as an Armor type, the Helos/music gave me a laugh---plus I've know the Duval types.<br>
DME---About ARVN.  Heard of that also---not in my outfit, but heard of it.  One thing to remember--and it applies to many other Armies as well and that's the unit and personal in many forighn armies are much more a reflection of their commander then is found in the US.<br>
Aggresive leader=aggresive troops.  Cowardly/causious leader=ditto for the troops.  Our system is designed to compensate for the poor commander, but others are not.  <br>
Cultrual reasons for this--but not here.<br>
Latin America is very simular.<br>
Examples abound on the valor of the indavidual ARVN&gt;<br>
I witnessed:<br>
Company Commander holding his mortor crew at gun point as he stood up in the open to return mortor fire.<br>
63 dead ARVN at an overrun 7th Cav compound=all the bodies were found on the vehicles or headed toward them and none were found running away from the vehilc locations.<br>
Two crews got their vehicles running and instead of running away, moved them to protect an adjacent Arty unit.  They all died fighting.<br>
That ARVN troop commander, wounded in the chest walking around the compound, holding his bleeding chest, and mumbling, &quot;all my poor soldiers are dead&quot; over and over as his crying wife followed him with the body of their dead five year old girl clutched in her arms.<br>
The ARVN Armor officer who's house was attacked at night.  Knowing he woud be killed, he went out to surrender and tell the VC that only his wife and seven kids  were in the house.  VC killed him, cut off his head, entered the house and machine gunned the unresisting wife and kids.<br>
I visited our units wounded in an ARVN hospital burn ward.  I never went again.  If that's the kind of care the wounded received, one needn't wonder that some might be more reluctant to end up there vice the care US received.<br>
Shoud also keep in mind that the Vietnamese had been fighting for twenty years longer then we had and they didn't get R&amp;R to Hong Kong and they didn't rotate home after one year.  It's easier to be &quot;gung ho&quot; for one year, or even two.  Little harder to do it for twenty.<br>
Remember my counterpart telling me, &quot;Relax, Maj. Andy, they were there yesterday, and they'll be there today.&quot;<br>
Finally.  I never saw or ever even heard of ARVN:<br>
---Refusing an order to conduct an operation<br>
---Being to high on drugs to go on operation<br>
---Fragging an officer<br>
It was a long time ago, in a place far away.  But I remember those people.  Someone needs to speak for them as they can't speak for themselves. Not all heros everyone, but neither were we and they never got a &quot;Welcome Home Parade.&quot;<br>
Nick or Andy
